=== Hypothesis ===

C1: Event1 always happens.
C2: C1 eventually holds.

C2 is True or False?

    <node id="event2" />
    <edge source="event1" target="event2" />
    <edge source="event2" target="event1" />
  </graph>
</graphml>
prediction_raw:
Step 1 — what the hypothesis asks
- C1: "Event1 always happens" means at every future point (from the point the claim is evaluated) event1 holds; i.e., event1 holds at all times (a global/always property).
- C2: "C1 eventually holds" means there is some time from which onward C1 is true (i.e., from some point on, event1 holds at every time).

Step 2 — examine the context
- Initially event2 happened (so at the initial moment event1 did not hold).
- Rule A: after event2, event1 must happen (so sometime after any occurrence of event2 there must be an occurrence of event1).
- Rule B: after event1, event2 must happen (so sometime after any occurrence of event1 there must be an occurrence of event2).

Step 3 — trace the sequences
- Starting with initial event2, rule A forces an event1 later.
- After that event1, rule B forces an event2 later.
- Repeating, the system must alternate: ... event2, event1, event2, event1, ...
- So event1 occurs infinitely often, but there are times where event2 occurs instead of event1. In particular, event1 is not true at every moment.

Step 4 — can C1 eventually hold?
- Suppose for contradiction that C2 were true: at some time t0, C1 holds forever after (i.e., from t0 onward event1 always holds).
- Then at time t0 (or immediately after) event1 must hold. But rule B then requires a subsequent event2 after that event1, contradicting that event1 holds at every future time.
- Therefore it's impossible for there to be a time after which event1 holds at all times.

Conclusion
- C2 is False.
